Events.html: 218 – Julia Maesa, aunt of the assassinated Caracalla, is banished to her home in Syria by the self-proclaimed emperor Macrinus and declares her 14-year old grandson Elagabalus, emperor of Rome.

Events.html: 1527 – The Florentines drive out the Medici for a second time and Florence re-establishes itself as a republic.

Events.html: 1532 – Sir Thomas More resigns as Lord Chancellor of England.

Events.html: 1568 – Mary, Queen of Scots, flees to England.

Events.html: 1584 – Santiago de Vera becomes sixth Governor-General of the Spanish colony of the Philippines.

Events.html: 1770 – A 14-year old Marie Antoinette marries 15-year-old Louis-Auguste who later becomes king of France.

Events.html: 1771 – The Battle of Alamance, a pre-American Revolutionary War battle between local militia and a group of rebels called The "Regulators", occurs in present-day Alamance County, North Carolina.

Events.html: 1811 – Peninsular War: The allies Spain, Portugal and United Kingdom, defeat the French at the Battle of Albuera.
Events.text: Peninsular War: The allies Spain, Portugal and United Kingdom, defeat the French at the Battle of Albuera.

Events.html: 1812 – Russian Field Marshal Mikhail Kutuzov signs the Treaty of Bucharest, ending the Russo-Turkish War. Bessarabia is annexed by Imperial Russia.

Events.html: 1822 – Greek War of Independence: The Turks capture the Greek town of Souli.
Events.text: Greek War of Independence: The Turks capture the Greek town of Souli.

Events.html: 1834 – The Battle of Asseiceira is fought, the last and decisive engagement of the Liberal Wars in Portugal.
Events.text: The Battle of Asseiceira is fought, the last and decisive engagement of the Liberal Wars in Portugal.

Events.html: 1843 – The first major wagon train heading for the Pacific Northwest sets out on the Oregon Trail with one thousand pioneers from Elm Grove, Missouri.

Events.html: 1866 – The U.S. Congress eliminates the half dime coin and replaces it with the five cent piece, or nickel.

Events.html: 1874 – A flood on the Mill River in Massachusetts destroys much of four villages and kills 139 people.

Events.html: 1877 – May 1877 political crisis in France.
Events.text: May 1877 political crisis in France.

Events.html: 1888 – Nikola Tesla delivers a lecture describing the equipment which will allow efficient generation and use of alternating currents to transmit electric power over long distances.

Events.html: 1891 – The International Electrotechnical Exhibition opens in Frankfurt, Germany, and will feature the world's first long distance transmission of high-power, three-phase electrical current (the most common form today).

Events.html: 1919 – A naval Curtiss aircraft NC-4 commanded by Albert Cushing Read leaves Trepassey, Newfoundland, for Lisbon via the Azores on the first transatlantic flight.
